\begin_layout Standard
Unless otherwise specified, the volume and surface terms in Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:semi-discrete-form"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are evaluated using a quadrature-free approach
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Atk96,Atk98"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Throughout this work, we employ a nodal basis, such that the element-local
 polynomial approximation of the solution is expanded as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{\kappa}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{b}}y_{\kappa}(x_{j})\phi_{j},\label{eq:solution-approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{b}$
\end_inset

 is the number of basis functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \phi_{1},\ldots,\phi_{n_{b}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are the basis functions, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{1},\ldots,x_{n_{b}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are the node coordinates.
 Its average over 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{y}_{\kappa}=\frac{1}{\left|\kappa\right|}\int_{\kappa}ydx,\label{eq:solution-element-average}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\kappa\right|$
\end_inset

 is the volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 In the evaluation of the second and third integrals in Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:semi-discrete-form"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the nonlinear convective flux can be approximated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F_{\kappa}}\approx\sum_{k=1}^{n_{c}}\mathcal{F}\left(y_{\kappa}\left(x_{k}\right)\right)\varphi_{k},\label{eq:flux-projection}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c}\geq n_{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{n_{c}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a set of (potentially different) polynomial basis functions.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c}=n_{b}$
\end_inset

 and the integration points are included in the set of solution nodes (e.g.,
 Gauss-Lobatto points for tensor-product elements), then pressure equilibrium
 is well-maintained (in an approximate sense)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Joh20_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, over-integration (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c}>n_{b}$
\end_inset

) is often necessary to minimize aliasing errors and improve stability.
 Unfortunately, standard over-integration, as defined in Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:flux-projection"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, causes a loss of pressure equilibrium and generation of spurious pressure
 oscillations at material interfaces
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Joh20_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Instead, Johnson and Kercher
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Joh20_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed the following approximation of the convective flux:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F_{\kappa}}\approx\sum_{k=1}^{n_{c}}\mathcal{F}\left(\widetilde{y}_{\kappa}\left(x_{k}\right)\right)\varphi_{k},\label{eq:modified-flux-projection}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}:\mathbb{R}^{m}\times\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is a modified state defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{y}\left(y,\widetilde{P}\right)=\left(\rho v_{1},\ldots,\rho v_{d},\widetilde{\rho u}\left(C_{1},\ldots,C_{n_{s}},\widetilde{P}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{k=1}^{d}\rho v_{k}v_{k},C_{1},\ldots,C_{n_{s}}\right)^{T}.\label{eq:interpolated-state-modified}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{P}$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial approximation of the pressure that interpolates onto the
 span of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \phi_{1},\ldots,\phi_{n_{b}}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{P}_{\kappa}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{b}}P\left(y_{\kappa}\left(x_{j}\right)\right)\phi_{j},
\]

\end_inset

and the modified internal energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\rho u}$
\end_inset

, is evaluated from the modified pressure and unmodified species concentrations.
 Interpolating the convective flux (including the numerical flux function)
 in this manner achieves pressure equilibrium both internally and between
 adjacent elements.
 Of course, with finite resolution, slight deviations from pressure equilibrium
 are inevitable; nevertheless, apart from severely underresolved computations,
 these deviations remain small and do not generate large-scale pressure
 oscillations that cause the solver to crash, which is not the case if standard
 flux interpolation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:flux-projection"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is employed.
 Additional information on the basic DG discretization, enforcement of boundary
 conditions, and nonlinear flux interpolation, as well as a detailed discussion
 of the conditions under which pressure oscillations are generated, can
 be found in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Joh20_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Minimum entropy principle
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:minimum-entropy-principle"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well-known that in the presence of discontinuities, weak solutions
 to general systems of hyperbolic conservation laws, including the multicomponen
t Euler equations, are not unique
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Har83_3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 As such, physical solutions are typically identified as those that satisfy
 entropy conditions, written as (in the absence of source terms)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial U}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\mathcal{F}^{s}\leq0,\label{eq:entropy-condition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U(y):\mathbb{R}^{m}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a given convex (mathematical) entropy function and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{s}(y):\mathbb{R}^{m}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding spatial entropy flux satisfying
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathsf{v}^{T}\frac{\partial\mathcal{F}}{\partial y}=\frac{\partial\mathcal{F}^{s}}{\partial y},
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{v}$
\end_inset

, the entropy variables, defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathsf{v}=\left(\frac{\partial U}{\partial y}\right)^{T}.
\]

\end_inset

The mapping from the conservative variables to the entropy variables is
 one-to-one and symmetrizes the system
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Moc80"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
Entropy solutions
\emph default
 are weak solutions that satisfy
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:entropy-condition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for all entropy/entropy-flux pairs.
 We also introduce the entropy potential and the corresponding entropy flux
 potential:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{F}^{p}\right)=\left(\mathsf{v}^{T}y-U,\mathsf{v}^{T}\mathcal{F}-\mathcal{F}^{s}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which will be used in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:entropy-stable-DGODE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For the multicomponent Euler equations, 
\begin_inset Formula $U=-\rho s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{s}=-\rho sv$
\end_inset

 form a common admissible entropy/entropy-flux pair
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gou20,Gio99"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T>0$
\end_inset

.
 Note the distinction between the mathematical entropy and the thermodynamic
 entropy (per unit volume); they are typically of opposite sign.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The conservation equation (for smooth solutions) for 
\begin_inset Formula $U=-\rho s$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by first combining the Gibbs relation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Tds=du-\sum_{i=1}^{n_{s}}g_{i}dY_{i}-\frac{P}{\rho^{2}}d\rho,
\]

\end_inset

with the transport equations for species mass fractions, density, and internal
 energy
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gou20,Gio99"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\frac{DY_{i}}{Dt} & =0,\;i=1,\ldots,n_{s},\\
\frac{D\rho}{Dt} & +\rho\nabla\cdot v=0,\\
\frac{Du}{Dt} & +\frac{P}{\rho}\nabla\cdot v=0,
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

to yield the specific entropy transport equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{Ds}{Dt}=0.\label{eq:entropy-transport-equation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then, using conservation of mass,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\left(\rho v\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset

the conservation equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $U=-\rho s$
\end_inset

 is obtained:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\rho s}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\left(\rho sv\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The corresponding entropy variables are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathsf{v}=\left(\frac{v_{1}}{T},\ldots,\frac{v_{d}}{T},-\frac{1}{T},\frac{g_{1}-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{k=1}^{d}v_{k}v_{k}}{T},\ldots,\frac{g_{n_{s}}-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{k=1}^{d}v_{k}v_{k}}{T}\right)^{T},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}=h_{i}-Ts_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the Gibbs function of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th species.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Review: Minimum entropy principle in the compressible, multicomponent, nonreacti
ng Euler equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:minimum-entropy-principle-nonreacting"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gouasmi et al.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gou20"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 recently proved a minimum entropy principle satisfied by entropy solutions
 to the multicomponent, nonreacting Euler equations, which means that the
 spatial minimum of the specific thermodynamic entropy is a nondecreasing
 function of time.
 In this subsection, we summarize the main steps of the proof, which itself
 builds on the proof by Tadmor
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tad86"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 of a minimum entropy principle in the monocomponent Euler equations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tadmor
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tad84"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 showed that by integrating
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:entropy-condition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 over the truncated cone 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{C}=\left\{ \left|x\right|\leq R+v_{\max}(t-\tau)|0\leq\tau\leq t\right\} $
\end_inset

 yields the following local inequality:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\left|x\right|\leq R}U\left(y(x,t)\right)dx\leq\int_{\left|x\right|\leq R+v_{\mathrm{max}}t}U\left(y(x,0)\right)dx,\label{eq:entropy-inequality-integral-local}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\max}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum speed in the domain at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 If we consider entropy/entropy-flux pairs of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(U,\mathcal{F}^{s}\right)=\left(-\rho f(s),-\rho vf(s)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:entropy-inequality-integral-local"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 then becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\left|x\right|\leq R}\rho(x,t)\cdot f\left(s\left(y(x,t)\right)\right)dx\geq\int_{\left|x\right|\leq R+v_{\mathrm{max}}t}\rho(x,0)\cdot f\left(s\left(y(x,0)\right)\right)dx.\label{eq:entropy-inequality-inject-f}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Consider the following choice for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{0}(s)=\min\left\{ s-s_{0},0\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the essential infimum of the specific thermodynamic entropy in the subdomain
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{R}=\left\{ \left|x\right|\leq R+v_{\max}t\right\} $
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{0}=\underset{\left|x\right|\leq R+v_{\max}t}{\text{Ess inf}}s(x,0).
\]

\end_inset

Although 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(s)$
\end_inset

 is not a smooth function of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, it can be written as the limit of a sequence of smooth functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(s)=\underset{\epsilon\rightarrow0}{\lim}f_{\epsilon}(s)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\epsilon}(s)$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gou20"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\epsilon}(s)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f_{0}(s-\mathfrak{s})g_{\epsilon}(\mathfrak{s})d\mathfrak{s},
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{\epsilon}(\mathfrak{s})=\frac{1}{\epsilon}\frac{\exp\left(-\frac{\mathfrak{s}^{2}}{\epsilon^{2}}\right)}{\sqrt{\pi}},\;\epsilon>0.
\]

\end_inset

The first and second derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\epsilon}(s)$
\end_inset

 satisfy the following conditions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
