\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lower bound on specific thermodynamic entropy
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:entropy-bound"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider two options for specifying 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 The first option is a 
\emph on
global
\emph default
 entropy bound
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zha12_2,Jia18,Wu21_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{b}(y)=\min\left\{ s\left(y(x)\right)\vert x\in\Omega\right\} ,\label{eq:global-entropy-bound-exact}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which can be evaluated once based on the initial condition, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}(x)$
\end_inset

, or updated at each time step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gou20"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Instead of calculating the true minimum via, for example, Newton's method,
 we either rely on user-specified information (e.g., the minimum entropy of
 the exact solution is known 
\emph on
a priori
\emph default
) or compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{b}(y)=\min\left\{ s\left(y(x)\right)\vert x\in\bigcup_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\mathcal{D_{\kappa}}\right\} .\label{eq:global-entropy-bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{b}(y_{0})$
\end_inset

, as given in Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:global-entropy-bound"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, is often the true minimum of 
\begin_inset Formula $s(y_{0})$
\end_inset

, especially in detonation wave simulations, in which the initial condition
 consists of piecewise constant regions.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second option is a 
\emph on
local
\emph default
 entropy bound, which should satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{b,\kappa}^{j+1}(y)\leq\min\left\{ \min\left\{ s\left(y_{\kappa}^{j}(x)\right)\vert x\in\mathcal{D_{\kappa}}\right\} ,\min\left\{ s\left(y_{\kappa}^{-,j}(x)\right)\vert x\in\mathcal{\partial D_{\kappa}}\right\} \right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

in order to ensure compatibility with Theorem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:CFL-condition-1D"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the limiting procedure, which enforces 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\kappa}^{j+1}(x)\in\mathcal{G}_{s_{b,\kappa}^{j+1}},\:\forall x\in\mathcal{D_{\kappa}}$
\end_inset

.
 Lv and Ihme
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lv15_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 introduced the following local entropy bound:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{b,\kappa}^{j+1}(y)=\min\left\{ \min\left\{ s\left(y_{\kappa}^{j}(x)\right)\vert x\in\kappa\right\} ,\min\left\{ s\left(y_{\kappa}^{-,j}(x)\right)\vert x\in\partial\kappa\right\} \right\} .\label{eq:lv-local-entropy-bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

They demonstrated that the local entropy bound
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:lv-local-entropy-bound"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can more effectively dampen overshoots and undershoots when the entropy
 varies significantly throughout the domain (e.g., when multiple discontinuities
 are present).
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
However, although Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:lv-local-entropy-bound"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is compatible with the framework described in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:entropy-bounded-DG-1D"

\end_inset

, physical or mathematical justification of such a local entropy bound seems
 to be lacking.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

However, we find that Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:lv-local-entropy-bound"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is often too restrictive, as will be illustrated in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:thermal-bubble"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we employ a different local entropy bound, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{b,\kappa}^{j+1}(y)=\min\left\{ s\left(y^{j}(x)\right)\vert x\in\kappa\cup\kappa_{L}\cup\kappa_{R}\right\} ,\label{eq:local-entropy-bound-exact}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is based on the local minimum entropy principle satisfied by exact
 entropy solutions (or discrete entropy solutions in the limit of infinite
 resolution).
 Specifically, the inequality
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s(y(x,t))\geq\min\left\{ s\left(y\left(x,t_{0}\right)\right)\vert x\in\kappa\cup\kappa_{L}\cup\kappa_{R}\right\} ,\quad t\in\left[t_{0},t_{0}+\Delta t\right],\label{eq:semi-discrete-minimum-entropy-principle}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

can be considered the semi-discrete analog of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:minimum-entropy-principle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R=h/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=\left[-h/2,h/2\right]$
\end_inset

, under the condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
in the inequality
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:minimum-entropy-principle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 yields, for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left[t_{0},t_{0}+\Delta t\right]$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s(y(x,t)) & \geq\min\left\{ s\left(y\left(x,t_{0}\right)\right)\vert\left|x\right|\leq\frac{h}{2}+v_{\max}t,\right\} ,\\
 & \geq\min\left\{ s\left(y\left(x,t_{0}\right)\right)\vert x\in\kappa\cup\kappa_{L}\cup\kappa_{R}\right\} ,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second inequality holds under the condition
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta tv_{\max}}{h}\leq1.\label{eq:CFL-condition-local-entropy-bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The RHS of Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:local-entropy-bound-exact"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is the fully discrete analog of the RHS of the inequality
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:semi-discrete-minimum-entropy-principle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 This property is imposed on the discrete solution as a means to suppress
 instabilities.
 A similar bound was employed by Dzanic and Witherden
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dza22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Trojak and Dzanic
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tro23"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in their entropy-based filtering framework.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:CFL-condition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, then it also satisfies
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:CFL-condition-local-entropy-bound"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta t\leq\frac{h}{2\lambda}\min\left\{ \theta_{L},\theta_{R}\right\} \leq\frac{h}{2\lambda}\leq\frac{h}{\lambda}\leq\frac{h}{v_{\max}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternate viewpoint draws from the generalized Riemann problem (GRP)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tor13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which differs from the 
\emph on
classical
\emph default
 Riemann problem by allowing for source terms and piecewise smooth (as opposed
 to piecewise constant) initial conditions.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\kappa_{L}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

 form the initial conditions of a GRP centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{L}$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\kappa_{R}}$
\end_inset

 form the initial conditions of a GRP centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Under the (potentially strong) assumption that exact solutions (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{L}^{\mathrm{GRP}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{R}^{\mathrm{GRP}}$
\end_inset

, respectively) to the GRPs exist, as well as the assumption that those
 solutions satisfy all entropy inequalities, the exact solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\kappa}^{\mathrm{ex}}$
\end_inset

, arising from the GRPs satisfies
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Har83_3"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{\kappa}U\left(y_{\kappa}^{\mathrm{ex}}(x,t)\right)\leq\int_{\kappa}U\left(y_{\kappa}(x,t_{0})\right)dx-\int_{t_{0}}^{t}\mathcal{F}^{s}\left(y_{R}^{\mathrm{GRP}}\left(x_{R},\tau\right)\right)d\tau+\int_{t_{0}}^{t}\mathcal{F}^{s}\left(y_{L}^{\mathrm{GRP}}\left(x_{L},\tau\right)\right)d\tau,
\]

\end_inset

at least before the local Riemann problems interact
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tor02"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U,\mathcal{F}^{s}\right)=\left(-\rho f_{0}(s),-\rho v_{1}f_{0}(s)\right)$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}=\min\left\{ s\left(y\left(x,t_{0}\right)\right)\vert x\in\kappa\cup\kappa_{L}\cup\kappa_{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

, the above inequality becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{\kappa}\rho\left(y_{\kappa}^{\mathrm{ex}}(x,t)\right)f_{0}\left(s\left(y_{\kappa}^{\mathrm{ex}}(x,t)\right)\right)dx & \geq & \int_{\kappa}\rho\left(y_{\kappa}(x,t_{0})\right)\min\left\{ s\left(y_{\kappa}(x,t_{0})\right)-s_{0},0\right\} dx\\
 &  & -\int_{t_{0}}^{t}\rho v_{1}\left(y_{R}^{\mathrm{GRP}}\left(x_{R},\tau\right)\right)\min\left\{ s\left(y_{R}^{\mathrm{GRP}}\left(x_{R},\tau\right)\right)-s_{0},0\right\} dx\\
 &  & +\int_{t_{0}}^{t}\rho v_{1}\left(y_{L}^{\mathrm{GRP}}\left(x_{L},\tau\right)\right)\min\left\{ s\left(y_{L}^{\mathrm{GRP}}\left(x_{L},\tau\right)\right)-s_{0},0\right\} dx,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the first term on the RHS clearly vanishes and the second and third
 terms vanish due to Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:minimum-entropy-principle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 As such, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $s\left(y_{\kappa}^{\mathrm{ex}}(x,t)\right)\geq s_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This property is then imposed on the discrete solution via the local entropy
 bound in Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:local-entropy-bound-exact"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To our knowledge, it is unclear whether the assumption that exact solutions
 to the GRP exist is valid (even for calorically perfect gases, let alone
 mixtures of thermally perfect gases).
 Semi-analytical methods for solving GRPs have been developed; see
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Chapter 19"
key "Tor13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a detailed description and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mon12"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a comparison of such methods.
 Discussions on exact solutions to the classical Riemann problem for mixtures
 of thermally perfect gases can be found in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bec01,Bec10"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To avoid finding the true minimum over a given element via an iterative
 procedure, we relax Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:local-entropy-bound-exact"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and instead compute 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{b,\kappa}^{j+1}(y)=\mathsf{c}\min\left\{ s\left(y^{j}(x)\right)\vert x\in\mathcal{D}_{\kappa}\cup\mathcal{D}_{\kappa_{L}}\cup\mathcal{D}_{\kappa_{R}}\right\} ,\label{eq:local-entropy-bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{c}\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

 is a relaxation parameter.
 The entropy limiter in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:limiting-procedure"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 remains valid since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\left(\overline{y}_{\kappa}^{j+1}\right)\geq\min\left\{ s\left(y^{j}(x)\right)\vert x\in\mathcal{D_{\kappa}}\cup\mathcal{D}_{\kappa}^{-}\right\} \geq\min\left\{ s\left(y^{j}(x)\right)\vert x\in\mathcal{D}_{\kappa}\cup\mathcal{D}_{\kappa_{L}}\cup\mathcal{D}_{\kappa_{R}}\right\} \geq s_{b,\kappa}^{j+1}(y).
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{c}<1$
\end_inset

, it can be useful to simultaneously account for a well-defined global entropy
 bound, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{b}$
\end_inset

, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{b,\kappa}^{j+1}(y)=\max\left\{ s_{b},\mathsf{c}\min\left\{ s\left(y^{j}(x)\right)\vert x\in\mathcal{D}_{\kappa}\cup\mathcal{D}_{\kappa_{L}}\cup\mathcal{D}_{\kappa_{R}}\right\} \right\} .\label{eq:local-global-entropy-bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this work, we simply choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{c}=1$
\end_inset

.
 An alternative approach for estimating the true minimum in an algebraic
 manner can be found in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lv15_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:local-entropy-bound"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{c}=1$
\end_inset

 yields the true minimum for 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

 if the solution nodes are located at the endpoints and included in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=\left[x_{L},x_{R}\right]$
\end_inset

, the basis functions are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{1}(x)=\frac{x_{R}-x}{x_{R}-x_{L}},\phi_{2}(x)=\frac{x-x_{L}}{x_{R}-x_{L}},
\]

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(x)\in(0,1),\:\forall x\in\left(x_{L},x_{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\kappa}(x)=y_{\kappa}\left(x_{1}\right)\phi_{1}(x)+y_{\kappa}\left(x_{2}\right)\phi_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 is a convex combination of the endpoint values of the solution.
 Then, by Lemma 2.1 in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zha12_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{x}s\left(y_{\kappa}(x)\right)=\min\left\{ s\left(y_{\kappa}\left(x_{1}\right)\right),s\left(y_{\kappa}\left(x_{2}\right)\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This is similarly true in two and three dimensions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Artificial viscosity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:artificial-viscosity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As will be demonstrated in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:shock-tube"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the proposed entropy-bounded DG method does not completely suppress smaller-sc
ale oscillations, especially in the presence of flow-field discontinuities.
 Therefore, artificial viscosity is employed in certain test cases in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:results-1D"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to more effectively dampen such oscillations.
 Specifically, the following dissipation term is added to the LHS of Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:semi-discrete-form"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Har13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\left(\mathcal{F}^{\mathrm{AV}}\left(y,\nabla y\right),\nabla\mathfrak{v}\right)_{\kappa},\label{eq:artificial-viscosity-integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}^{\mathrm{AV}}(y,\nabla y)=\nu_{\mathrm{AV}}\nabla y,
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\mathrm{AV}}\geq0$
\end_inset

 denoting the artificial viscosity.
 The artificial viscosity is computed as
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Joh20_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu_{\mathrm{AV}}=\left(C_{\mathrm{AV}}+S_{\mathrm{AV}}\right)\left(\frac{h^{2}}{p+1}\left|\frac{\partial T}{\partial y}\cdot\frac{\mathcal{R}\left(y,\nabla y\right)}{T}\right|\right).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
which is similar to the form in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Joh20_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{AV}}$
\end_inset

 is a user-defined coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mathrm{AV}}$
\end_inset

 is a shock sensor based on intra-element variations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chi19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}\left(y,\nabla y\right)$
\end_inset

 is the strong form of the residual
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:conservation-law-strong-form"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fully-discrete-form-average-unexpanded"
